  -- Class / Martial Movement
  [1879428104] = {
      [1] = {
        "Obtain Martial Movement";
      };
      [2] = {
        "Demand an explanation from Brom";
      };
      [3] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 27 - On this page, Brom discusses the importance of knowing when to dodge an oncoming attack. 'Depending on the attack's direction,' he writes, 'you may wish to duck! However, if your foe has made an overhead swing with some heavy object, a quick side-step may be more appropriate.'";
      };
      [4] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 33 - Brom spends most of the available space on this page describing a particularly memorable brawl from his younger days. 'You should have seen it,' he writes. 'There were chairs flying through the air, but they were like so many wisps of cloud to us, for nary a one could touch us!'";
      };
      [5] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 34 - On this page, Brom has sketched a diagram that contains entirely too many feet to follow. 'As you can see,' he writes, 'it is very important to keep your feet moving while you are in the thick of the fighting.'";
      };
      [6] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 35 - On this page, Brom discusses a number of different feints you can use to disorient your opponents, including such diversions as the Whoops Not That Way, the Over Here Not There, and the Too Fast For You.";
      };
      [7] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 36 - On this page, Brom claims to have invented the well-known adage that the best defence is a good offence. As far as you can tell, this is not true. Towards the bottom of the page, Brom claims that the best offence is a good defence, just in case.";
      };
      [8] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 52 - On this page, Brom suggests that you practice your most agile manoeuvres on the windiest day you can find. 'That way,' he writes, 'you'll be able to move even faster when the air is still and calm!'";
      };
      [9] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 56 - On this page, Brom floats a disturbing hypothetical situation. 'In the event you find yourself engaged in combat with a brawler who is also familiar with the contents of this book, you may find yourself locked in a perpetual dance of dodging and weaving, with neither combatant able to land a successful blow!' Brom has no further advice to counter this situation; he apparently just thought it was interesting.";
      };
      [10] = {
        "Martial Movement, Page 58 - On this page, Brom notes the importance of maintaining complete focus when engaged in the middle of a whirling storm of battle. 'Only a heightened sense of awareness can enable you to side-step whatever projectiles might be coming your way,' he writes. Toward the bottom of the page he seems to contradict himself. 'Sometimes you might need some luck on your side,' he notes. 'But reading such instructive texts as these is ultimately the most important thing, of course. Thanks for buying my book!'";
      };
  };
  -- Class / Knowledge of Kicks
  [1879428111] = {
      [1] = {
        "Obtain Knowledge of Kicks";
      };
      [2] = {
        "Ask Brom why his treatise is missing so many pages";
      };
      [3] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 7 - On this page, Brom recommends a simple means of improving the accuracy of your kicks: by setting an apple atop a wooden fence-post, closing your eyes, and attempting to strike the apple from its place with your foot. 'If you are able to do this,' Brom writes, 'you can graduate to smaller apples and higher posts.'";
      };
      [4] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 10 - On this page, Brom engages in a lengthy detour discussing punches instead of kicks. At the bottom of the page he recommends that you consult another of his books, 'The Art of the Perfect Punch,' for even more melee-related material. You wonder if that book is full of information about kicks, and who suggested Brom write these books in the first place.";
      };
      [5] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 12 - On this page, Brom has drawn a number of diagrams intended to demonstrate the proper form of three powerful kicks. Unfortunately, his artistic skills are rather less than his brawling prowess, and the drawings are impossible to understand.";
      };
      [6] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 18 - On this page, Brom details the problems and pitfalls of attempting to strike an opponent with your foot while jumping. 'Unless you are quite fast,' he writes, 'your opponent may be able to grab your leg during the approach, and then where will you be? Leave this manoeuvre to the experts!'";
      };
      [7] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 19 - On this page, Brom continues his apparently heart-felt prohibition against jump-kicks. 'Trust me, dear reader,' he writes, 'you do not want to jump at someone with your foot extended, only to have them grab you out of midair. It would be humiliating... I assume.' You suspect the author of Knowledge of Kicks had a bad experience executing this sort of manoeuvre at some point in his history.";
      };
      [8] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 25 - On this page, Brom discusses the importance of kicking with both your left and right legs. 'But not at the same time,' he concludes.";
      };
      [9] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 35 - On this page, Brom compares the art of brawling with your feet to the practice of dancing. 'But not like they do it at court,' he continues. 'Brawling with your feet is much nearer the sort of dance you'd find at a country inn... and more fun, too!'";
      };
      [10] = {
        "Knowledge of Kicks, Page 37 - On this page, Brom recommends the purchase of another of his books, Martial Movement. Between the covers of that 'fine investment' he promises to explain a number of manoeuvres that will allow you to dodge the type of kicks you have learned from this tome. 'But don't worry,' he writes, 'for your opponents will not have read it.'";
      };
  };
  -- Class / The Art of the Perfect Punch
  [1879428116] = {
      [1] = {
        "Obtain The Art of the Perfect Punch";
      };
      [2] = {
        "Express your dissatisfaction to Brom Hawksbeard in Bree Jail";
      };
      [3] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 6 - On this page, Brom discusses a number of openings a brawler might use to begin a fight. Chief among these is the time-tested 'look at the thrush!' manoeuvre, in which a brawler pretends to hold a tiny bird in the left hand and strikes out suddenly with the right.";
      };
      [4] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 7 - On this page, Brom lists a number of follow-up moves to use against opponents who have been consumed with rage following the successful execution of the 'look at the thrush!' manoeuvre detailed on a previous page. Most of these seem to rely upon beating a hasty retreat.";
      };
      [5] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 15 - On this page, Brom goes into great detail on the differences between a 'thump' and a 'wallop.' As terms of art, they leave much to be desired.";
      };
      [6] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 19 - On this page, Brom asks the question 'Is the most valuable punch the one you never need to throw?' His answer: 'no.'";
      };
      [7] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 22 - On this page, Brom lists a number of vulnerable spots a skilled brawler might target with punches in order to debilitate his opponents. Unfortunately, his understanding of anatomy is less than thorough, and most of his advice only applies to humanoid opponents.";
      };
      [8] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 23 - On this page, Brom suggests that if you intend to brawl with spiders or other crawling insects, you should purchase another of his books, 'Knowledge of Kicks,' for valuable advice on dealing with such creatures. 'I will not here describe what type of attack you will need,' he writes, 'but it is not a punch of any kind!' You suspect he may be referring to kicks, but with Brom it is hard to say.";
      };
      [9] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 24 - On this page, Brom notes that many brawlers never master the art of the perfect punch, despite studying from the best trainers Middle-earth has on offer. 'This reflects poorly on the student, and not on the teachers,' he insists.";
      };
      [10] = {
        "The Art of the Perfect Punch, Page 49 - On this page, Brom discusses the importance of landing successive blows with alternating fists. You wonder why he waited until page 49 to describe this significant element of combat.";
      };
  };
